glen herrmannsfeldt <gah@ugcs.caltech.edu> writes:
> When I was using a real PDP-10 there were stories of someone who
> could type fast enough on a fast terminal to crash the system.
> That is, overflow the terminal input buffer.

I never heard of such a problem on ITS.
The terminals there were connected various ways,
including homebrew multiplexors, DL10 and DTE20,
virtual network terminals on CHAOS and on TCP/IP,
and on the AI (KA) machine by a 10-11 interface 
to Knight's frame buffer system (bitmap graphics
display consoles to the PDP-10 memory, with the
fancy keyboards that have been mentioned in
another thread).

So I am guessing that any crashes from people typing too 
fast were bugs in the DEC software, rather than some
necessary lossage of the PDP-10 hardware.
